<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="49" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,648,190,216]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Relationships and characterization:</emphasis>
—This species is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus f., 1782" authorityName="Linnaeus f." authorityYear="1782" box="[1187,1436,191,216]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Muellera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="virgilioides">
<emphasis box="[1187,1436,191,216]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Muellera virgilioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from which it differs by its fruits lanceolate, chartaceous and with superior margin nerviform, bracts and bracteoles without secretory cavities, calyx with triangular vexillary lobe, anthers ovoid and glabrous, ovary glabrous on central portion, beyond seeds reniform, elliptic in cross-section and with orbicular hilum. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus f., 1782" authorityName="Linnaeus f." authorityYear="1782" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Muellera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="virgilioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">M. virgilioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the fruits are woody, oblong-elliptic to elliptic, conspicuously thickened on the superior margin, and constricted between the seeds, the bracts and bracteoles have secretory cavities, the calyx has rounded vexillary lobes, the anthers are ovate to orbicular and indumented, the ovary is fully indumented, and the seeds are oblong, linear in cross section, and have a elliptic hilum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="49" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,453,499,525]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Conservation status</emphasis>
:—According to 
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" box="[664,827,500,526]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" refId="ref5420" refString="IUCN (2001) The IUCN red list threatened species, version 2010. 4. IUCN Red List Unit, Cambridge U. K. Available from http: www. iucnredlist. org (accessed: 20 June 2011)." type="book" year="2001">IUCN (2001)</bibRefCitation>
criteria, the species should be considered “Near Threatened” (NT) because the areas of its occurrence (Caatinga vegetation and montane forests) have been under intense pressure of deforestation for the extraction of timber.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
